President Biden convened a call with the Governors of Louisiana, Alabama, and Mississippi, FEMA Administrator Deanne Criswell, Homeland Security Advisor Liz Sherwood-Randall, and Director of Intergovernmental Affairs Julie Rodriguez to discuss preparations for Hurricane Ida. Ida is projected to strengthen to a Category 4 Hurricane and make landfall on the Gulf Coast on Sunday, the 16th anniversary of Hurricane Katrina. The President approved an Emergency Declaration for the State of Louisiana. The call focused on the potential impacts of Ida, including storm surge, heavy rainfall, and hurricane-force winds. The Governors discussed their actions to pre-position resources and initiate evacuation operations. Governor Edwards emphasized the importance of preventing the spread of COVID-19 in shelters. The President stressed the importance of getting vaccinated and preparing for the storm. FEMA is pre-positioning resources in the region, including food, water, generators, and personnel. The U.S. Coast Guard and U.S. Army Corps of Engineers are also deploying resources. The President assured impacted communities of the full support of the Federal government.